SIMPLE: earthquake
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Earthquake
<hw>Earth"quake`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A shaking,
trembling, or concussion of the earth, due to subterranean causes, often
accompanied by a rumbling noise. The wave of shock sometimes traverses
half a hemisphere, destroying cities and many thousand lives; -- called
also <altname>earthdin</altname>, <altname>earthquave</altname>, and
<altname>earthshock</altname>.</def><-- also temblor, tremor -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Earthquake alarm</b></col>, <cd>a bell signal constructed
to operate on the theory that a few seconds before the occurrence of an
earthquake the magnet temporarily loses its power.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Earthquake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Earthquake
<hw>Earth"quake`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Like, or characteristic of, an
earthquake; loud; startling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>earthquake</qex> voice of victory.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Earthquave</ent>⟦br⟧
